  Good Venky üî•
This is very important to understand clearly.

I‚Äôll explain in **simple step-by-step flow**.

---

# 1Ô∏è‚É£ What is `props`?

üëâ `props` means:

> Data passed from parent to child component.

Example:

```jsx
function Welcome(props) {
  return <h1>Hello {props.name}</h1>;
}

function App() {
  return <Welcome name="Venky" />;
}
```

Here:

* `name` is a prop
* Passed using attribute
* Accessed using `props.name`

---

# 2Ô∏è‚É£ What is `children`?

üëâ `children` is a **special prop**.

It contains:

> Whatever you write between opening and closing tags.

Example:

```jsx
function Box(props) {
  return <div>{props.children}</div>;
}

function App() {
  return (
    <Box>
      <h2>Hello Venky</h2>
    </Box>
  );
}
```

Here:

* `<h2>Hello Venky</h2>` is automatically stored in
* `props.children`

---

# 3Ô∏è‚É£ Core Difference (Very Important)

| `props`                            | `children`                                |
| ---------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------- |
| Passed as attributes               | Passed between tags                       |
| You define the name                | React automatically gives name `children` |
| Can pass numbers, strings, objects | Usually JSX (UI content)                  |
| Example: `name="Venky"`            | Example: `<Box>content</Box>`             |

---

# 4Ô∏è‚É£ Internally What Happens?

### Normal props:

```jsx
<Welcome name="Venky" />
```

Becomes:

```js
Welcome({ name: "Venky" })
```

---

### Children:

```jsx
<Box>
  <h2>Hello</h2>
</Box>
```

Becomes:

```js
Box({
  children: <h2>Hello</h2>
})
```

So actually:

üëâ `children` is ALSO a prop
üëâ But it is automatically created by React

---

# 5Ô∏è‚É£ You Can Use Both Together

Example:

```jsx
function Card({ title, children }) {
  return (
    <div>
      <h2>{title}</h2>
      {children}
    </div>
  );
}

function App() {
  return (
    <Card title="Profile">
      <p>This is profile content</p>
    </Card>
  );
}
```

Here:

* `title` ‚Üí normal prop
* `<p>` ‚Üí children prop

---

# 6Ô∏è‚É£ Simple Real-Life Analogy

Think like this:

```
props = data
children = content
```

Example:

```
Card
  title = "Profile"  (data)
  children = <p>Details</p>  (content)
```

---

# 7Ô∏è‚É£ When to Use What?

‚úÖ Use normal props when:

* Passing values
* Passing configuration
* Passing flags
* Passing functions

‚úÖ Use children when:

* Passing UI content
* Building reusable layout components
* Creating wrappers

---

# Final Simple Definition

üëâ All children are props
üëâ But not all props are children

Children is just a **special prop name automatically handled by React**.

